 :tx/rationale "ASSESSMENT FINDING: Saw-tooth Convergence Model Not Observable — The saw-tooth invariant predicts F(S) oscillation: spec growth (surprise) causes dip, verification (consolidation) causes recovery. After 13 sessions at F(S) 0.62 ± 0.02, we see neither dip nor recovery — just flatness. Three possible explanations: (1) Specification and verification grow at the same rate, maintaining constant ratio — unlikely given 265 untested INVs. (2) Oscillation period exceeds 13 sessions — possible but not useful. (3) F(S) has a structural ceiling below theoretical maximum — most concerning. The likely explanation: each session adds ~10 specs and ~10 verifications, creating a pseudo-steady state. To break equilibrium and empirically test the saw-tooth model, the project needs a verification-only sprint (3-5 sessions, zero new specs). If F(S) rises to 0.75+ after the sprint, the saw-tooth is validated. If it stays at 0.62, the F(S) formulation may have anti-correlated components creating a structural maximum. This is a falsifiable prediction about the system's own convergence model. VERIFICATION: Execute verification sprint, measure F(S) before and after. Predicted outcome: F(S) rises to 0.72-0.78. If falsified: revise F(S) component weights or formulation. INTERACTS WITH: F(S) stagnation diagnosis (same underlying issue), verification sprint proposal (the intervention), structural ceiling risk (the alternative hypothesis). TRACES TO: ADR-FOUNDATION-014 (convergence thesis), ADR-FOUNDATION-020 (falsification-first)."
